{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645791"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:21:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:21:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18132"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18132"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.14,0.14,0,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26867"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the plastic surgery clinic requiring tendon grafting following a hand injury. The surgeon examines both of her forearms by asking her to oppose her thumb and fifth finger while flexing her wrist. The test reveals a thin, cord-like structure in the midline of her right wrist, but this structure is absent on the left side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is being tested in this examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Palmaris longus","Flexor digitorum superficialis","Flexor carpi ulnaris","Pronator teres","Flexor carpi radialis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalmaris longus\u003C/strong\u003E is being tested in this examination. This muscle is notable for being absent in approximately 15% of people. Bilateral absence is found in 8 to 16% of individuals and unilateral absence in 4 to 14%, which explains its unilateral absence in this patient. When present, it appears as a thin, cord-like tendon in the midline of the wrist during flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor carpi radialis\u003C/strong\u003E appears as a thick tendon on the radial side of the wrist and is consistently present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor carpi ulnaris\u003C/strong\u003E inserts into the pisiform bone on the ulnar side of the wrist\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor digitorum superficialis\u003C/strong\u003E lies deep to palmaris longus and its tendons are not visible superficially at the wrist\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPronator teres\u003C/strong\u003E lies in the proximal forearm and does not have a visible tendon at the wrist\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe palmaris longus is commonly harvested for tendon grafting procedures because it can be removed without significant functional deficit to the patient. It originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts into the palmar aponeurosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The palmaris longus muscle is absent in approximately 15% of the population without affecting hand function.","The palmaris longus is a weak wrist flexor that lies superficially in the anterior compartment of the forearm.","The palmaris longus tendon serves as a useful surgical donor graft due to its superficial location and expendable nature."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18132"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T16:06:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T16:07:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78401"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emed